Five truths about terrorism
SÃO PAULO – American politics are hostage to terrorism.
In December 2015, polls showed that one American in six, or about 16% of the population, now placed terrorism at the top of the country's problems – a 3% increase in a month.
For the past ten years, never so many Americans had been so concerned about terrorism, even if their number is still very much lower than the 46% recorded in the aftermath of the 9/11 attacks in 2001.
The consequences of this evolution in public opinion were felt most strongly in the Republican primary for the presidential election.
Donald Trump's candidacy, with its particularly inflammatory (if not incendiary) anti-Muslim rhetoric, has undoubtedly benefited from this.
Certain politicians authorize themselves to speak of the battle against terrorism as the "Third World War".
Terrorism is a problem for the United States, as shown by the San Bernardino attack in California in December of last year.
But the presidential election candidates, like some media who follow the old adage "if it bleeds, it makes the headlines", have exaggerated the proportions.
To put terrorism back in its true perspective, Americans should – like others – keep the following considerations in mind:
Terrorism is a kind of theater.
Terrorists are more concerned with holding attention and monopolizing political news than with the number of their victims in itself.
The Islamic State (IS) takes great care of its staging.
The barbaric beheadings broadcast on social networks are intended to destabilize and scandalize – and thus to monopolize attention.
To exaggerate their consequences and make headlines with each terrorist action, it's playing the terrorists' game.
The terrorism is not the most severe threat hanging over the populations of developed countries.
Terrorism kills a lot less than road accidents or smoking.
From this point of view, terrorism is not a real threat – either major or minor.
There are more chances of being struck by lightning than being killed by a terrorist.
The probability that an American citizen will be assassinated by a terrorist is, according to experts, one in 3.5 million.
Americans are more likely to die in their bathtub (a probability of 1 in 950,000), from an appliance-related accident (a probability of 1 in 1.5 million), by a deer or elk crossing the road (a probability of 1 in 2 million), or in a commercial airliner crash (a probability of 1 in 2.9 million).
Six thousand Americans die every year while driving and texting or talking on their mobile phone.
This is several hundred times the number who die from terrorism.
Radical Islamic terrorism kills fewer Americans than attacks carried out by disgruntled employees or mass shootings at universities or schools.
Terrorism is not World War III.
Global terrorism is not new.
It often takes one generation to extinguish a wave of terrorism.
At the beginning of the 20th century, the anarchist movement killed a number of heads of state in the name of utopian ideals.
During the sixties and seventies, the Red Brigades and the Red Army Faction, both from the "autonomous" left, hijacked planes outside national borders and kidnapped or killed business leaders or political leaders (but also ordinary citizens).
Today's extremist jihadists are an old political phenomenon draped in a religious costume.
Many of their leaders are not fundamentalists in the traditional sense, but people with a destroyed identity by globalization, who are seeking meaning in the imaginary and pure community of an Islamic caliphate.
It will take time and effort to defeat them, but the restrictive nature of ISIS limits its scope of attraction.
Its sectarian attacks already prevent it from addressing all Muslims, let alone Hindus, Christians, or other believers.
ISIS will eventually be defeated, just like the transnational terrorist groups that preceded it were.
Terrorism is like jiu-jitsu.
The weakest of the two adversaries uses the strength of the stronger to defeat it.
No terrorist organization has the power of a state, and few terrorist movements have been able to overthrow one.
But if they succeed in shocking and provoking enough citizens of a state to push them to vain actions, they can hope to gain an advantage.
In 2001, Al-Qaida was able to lure the Americans to Afghanistan.
The EI was born in the ruins of the US-led invasion of Iraq, which followed the intervention in Afghanistan.
To conquer terrorism, we need intelligent power (smart power).
Intelligent power is capable of combining the coercive power (hard power) of the army and police with the influence power (soft power) of seduction and persuasion.
The influence power is also necessary if we want to vaccinate those on the periphery and those who are irreducible are looking to recruit.
That is why the attention given to the narrative of events and the way the action of the United States is commented on social networks is also important and necessary as precision airstrikes.
The rhetoric of confrontation, which points at Muslims and alienates the goodwill that would allow us to obtain crucial information, puts us all in danger.
Reason why the anti-Islam stance of some current presidential election candidates is so counter-productive.
The terrorist issue is serious, and it deserves to be placed among the priorities of our intelligence and police services, our armed forces, and our diplomacy.
It is an important factor in our foreign policy.
And it is essential to keep weapons of mass destruction out of terrorists' reach.
But we must not fall into the trap set by the terrorists.
Let's not fill the theater where events led by brutes and thugs take place.
If we leave them the great stage of our public speech, we will diminish the quality of our civic life and reveal our priorities.
Our strength would then be used against us.
